we've never seen him capture a bush baby.

00:53:02.830 --> 00:53:04.380
But what's interesting is you see

00:53:04.380 --> 00:53:07.400
that the third top hunter there,

00:53:07.400 --> 00:53:09.760
at least in terms of prey captures, Lupin,

00:53:09.760 --> 00:53:12.250
has fallen quite low because he does seem

00:53:12.250 --> 00:53:13.870
to specialize on bush babies.

00:53:13.870 --> 00:53:15.950
So the females really didn't
change positions at all,

00:53:15.950 --> 00:53:17.610
they're still in the top 10,

00:53:17.610 --> 00:53:19.440
but you do see a lot of variation.

00:53:19.440 --> 00:53:21.470
So that's something that
we're looking at now,

00:53:21.470 --> 00:53:23.630
and so, I wanted to talk just a little bit

00:53:23.630 --> 00:53:26.670
about what females can provide

00:53:26.670 --> 00:53:29.853
in terms of transfer or sharing.

00:53:31.600 --> 00:53:33.040
And we...

00:53:33.040 --> 00:53:37.150
So far this is still
preliminary to some degree.

00:53:37.150 --> 00:53:39.910
We've looked at sharing or
food transfer by females,

00:53:39.910 --> 00:53:42.650
and again I'm considering
David's categories

00:53:42.650 --> 00:53:44.780
of active transfer, passive transfer

00:53:44.780 --> 00:53:47.360
and scrounging but tolerated scrounging,

00:53:47.360 --> 00:53:50.210
and I'm not considering
a theft in this category.

00:53:50.210 --> 00:53:53.750
Females actually shared
with other individuals

00:53:53.750 --> 00:53:55.660
more often they did with their offspring.

00:53:55.660 --> 00:53:59.110
So that's something that
we're exploring right now.

00:53:59.110 --> 00:54:03.020
And, basically, I would
argue that females,

00:54:03.020 --> 00:54:07.960
as Rebecca has pointed out,
should be considered as well.

00:54:07.960 --> 00:54:10.390
And, finally, I'll just
move on to my last slide

00:54:10.390 --> 00:54:13.040
